    "Model Choice": "A fully-connected MLP (e.g., 4–6 layers, 64–128 units, tanh or sin activations) mapping (x,y) → u. SIREN (sin activations with proper initialization) is preferred for better representation of higher-frequency content typical in Poisson solutions. The network is differentiable, enabling automatic computation of ∂²u/∂x² and ∂²u/∂y² for the residual loss. This architecture suits the smooth, elliptic nature of the PDE and requires no mesh.",
    "Training Strategy": "Total loss L = λ_r · L_res + λ_b · L_bc where L_res = (1/N_r) Σ|r(x_i,y_i)|² over N_r interior collocation points (sampled uniformly or via Latin Hypercube in Ω) and L_bc = (1/N_b) Σ|u(x_j,y_j) - g(x_j,y_j)|² over N_b boundary points (sampled uniformly on each edge). Use Adam optimizer (lr ~1e-3) for initial convergence followed by L-BFGS for fine-tuning. Set λ_b >> λ_r (e.g., λ_b = 100) or use a hard constraint for Dirichlet BCs by constructing û = g + d(x,y)·N(x,y) where d(x,y) is a signed distance function that vanishes on ∂Ω, eliminating L_bc entirely. Resample collocation points periodically to reduce overfitting to specific point sets.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "(1) Unspecified domain geometry, f, and g prevent concrete implementation; placeholder assumptions may yield misleading results. (2) Spectral bias may cause poor approximation of high-frequency features in f or g; mitigated by SIREN or Fourier feature embeddings. (3) Soft boundary enforcement with insufficient λ_b leads to boundary leakage; hard constraints are more robust. (4) Insufficient collocation point density in regions where f varies rapidly causes large residual pockets. (5) Without an analytical or numerical reference solution, validation relies solely on residual norms, which can be small yet mask significant solution error (spectral bias). A finite-difference or FEM benchmark on a coarse grid is recommended for sanity checking."
