    "Problem Formalization": "The 1D viscous Burgers equation is ∂u/∂t + u ∂u/∂x = ν ∂²u/∂x² on x ∈ [0, L] with periodic BCs u(0,t) = u(L,t) and known IC u(x,0) = u₀(x). The viscosity ν is small, producing a steep internal (shock-like) layer of width δ ~ O(ν/|Δu|), where Δu is the velocity jump across the layer. The solution must be resolved at scale δ within the budget of 20,000 collocation points and 30,000 optimizer steps. Missing specifications: the domain length L, final time T, and exact value of ν (only that it is 'small enough' for layer formation). These affect the required point density; the workflow below is parameterized by ν and L.",
    "Physics Constraints": "Three loss terms: (1) PDE residual L_r = (1/N_r) Σ|∂u_θ/∂t + u_θ ∂u_θ/∂x − ν ∂²u_θ/∂x²|² at collocation points; (2) IC loss L_ic = (1/N_ic) Σ|u_θ(x,0) − u₀(x)|²; (3) Periodic BC loss L_bc = (1/N_bc) Σ|u_θ(0,t) − u_θ(L,t)|² + |∂u_θ/∂x(0,t) − ∂u_θ/∂x(L,t)|². Total loss: L = w_r L_r + w_ic L_ic + w_bc L_bc with w_ic, w_bc ≫ w_r initially (e.g., 100:1) to enforce constraints firmly. The periodicity constraint is critical: both u and ∂u/∂x must match at the boundary.",
    "Model Choice": "A fully-connected network with Fourier feature embeddings, chosen because: (a) sinusoidal input embeddings naturally enforce periodicity when frequencies are integer multiples of 2π/L; (b) high-frequency embeddings up to k_max ~ 2π/δ ≈ 2π|Δu|/ν give the network spectral capacity to represent the O(δ)-width layer. Architecture: input (x,t) → Fourier embedding layer with m=64 frequencies (k = 1,2,...,m × 2π/L) producing 128 features → 4 hidden layers of width 128 with tanh activation → scalar output u. Total parameters ~70,000, well within memory budget. The Fourier embedding bandwidth k_max = 128π/L must satisfy 128π/L ≥ 2π/δ, i.e., L/δ ≤ 64, which for δ ~ ν/|Δu| means the method resolves layers when ν/|Δu| ≥ L/64. If ν is smaller, the embedding bandwidth must increase (increase m) or adaptive sampling must compensate.",
    "Training Strategy": "Two-phase training within 30,000 steps. Phase 1 (steps 1–10,000): Uniform random sampling of 15,000 residual points + 2,500 IC points + 2,500 BC points (total 20,000 in memory). Adam optimizer, lr=1e-3. Phase 2 (steps 10,001–30,000): Residual-adaptive resampling every 2,000 steps — recompute PDE residuals on a candidate pool, then retain 8,000 points where |residual| is largest (concentrated near the internal layer of width δ ~ ν/|Δu|) plus 7,000 uniform points + 2,500 IC + 2,500 BC. This ensures effective point spacing near the layer of Δx_eff ~ (5δ × T)/(8000) in the layer band, achieving ~5+ points across the δ-wide layer when 8000 ≳ 5T/δ, i.e., δ ≳ 5T/8000. Learning rate cosine-annealed to 1e-5 in Phase 2. Gradient clipping at norm 1.0 stabilizes training near steep gradients. Causal time-marching weighting: weight the PDE residual at time t by exp(−ε·(T−t)) with ε decreasing from 10 to 0.1 over training, so the network learns early-time smooth solutions before late-time steep layers.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "Primary risk: under-resolved internal layer. Monitor: (1) PDE residual magnitude near the expected layer location — if max|residual|/mean|residual| > 10³ after Phase 1, the layer is under-resolved. (2) Compare u_θ(x,t) against a coarse finite-difference reference solution (e.g., 1000-point Godunov scheme) at t=T; if relative L² error > 5%, the PINN has failed to capture the layer. (3) Track the effective layer width from the PINN solution: compute |∂u/∂x|_max and estimate δ_PINN = |Δu|/|∂u/∂x|_max; if δ_PINN > 2ν/|Δu|, the layer is smeared (under-resolved). (4) If the periodic BC loss does not decrease below 1e-6, the network may be violating periodicity at the layer, indicating insufficient capacity or sampling. Mitigation: if any monitor triggers, increase Fourier embedding frequencies and allocate more Phase 2 adaptive points to the layer region, at the cost of fewer uniform background points."
