    "Physics Constraints": "Primary constraint: PDE residual loss R = ∂u_θ/∂t - ε²Δu_θ + F'(u_θ) ≈ 0 enforced at collocation points. Secondary constraints: (1) Initial condition loss ‖u_θ(x,0) - u₀(x)‖² — essential for parabolic problems. (2) Boundary condition loss — form depends on unspecified BCs. (3) Energy dissipation: the Ginzburg-Landau free energy E[u] = ∫[ε²|∇u|²/2 + F(u)]dx must be non-increasing in time; enforcing dE/dt ≤ 0 as a soft constraint stabilizes training and enforces physical consistency. (4) Boundedness: solution should remain in [-1,1] for standard double-well; a penalty for |u_θ|>1 prevents unphysical excursions. (5) Interface motion by mean curvature: at late times, interfaces move proportionally to curvature — this asymptotic property can serve as an auxiliary validation constraint.",
    "Model Choice": "A modified MLP with Fourier feature embeddings (sinusoidal positional encoding of inputs) is recommended. Justification: (1) Sharp interfaces require high-frequency representation — Fourier features mitigate spectral bias and enable the network to represent steep gradients. (2) The reaction term u³-u is smooth but stiff, requiring expressive nonlinear mappings that standard MLPs provide. (3) Domain decomposition via separate networks per time-window (time-marching) reduces the complexity each sub-network must learn and naturally handles causality. Alternative: SIREN (sinusoidal activation networks) for implicit representation of interface geometry, but Fourier features with ReLU are more stable under gradient-based training. If the domain is rectangular, consider periodic activations for periodic BCs. A multi-scale architecture with skip connections helps capture both bulk phase behavior (u≈±1) and narrow interface layers simultaneously.",
    "Training Strategy": "(1) Causal time-marching: train sequentially on time windows [0,T₁], [T₁,T₂], etc., using the trained solution at t=T_k as the initial condition for the next window — this prevents temporal error accumulation and respects the parabolic causality structure. (2) Adaptive collocation sampling: periodically re-sample with higher density where |∇u_θ| is large (interface regions) and where |R| is large (residual-guided refinement). (3) Loss weighting: use gradient-based adaptive weighting (e.g., GradNorm or NeurIPS-style learning rate annealing) to balance PDE residual, IC, and BC losses, since the stiff reaction term produces gradients orders of magnitude larger than the diffusion term. (4) Optimization: Adam with learning rate 1e-3 → 1e-4 cosine schedule; if instability persists, switch to L-BFGS for fine-tuning in each time window. (5) Curriculum on ε: if ε is small, start training with a larger effective ε and anneal downward to improve convergence. (6) Energy dissipation penalty: add λ_E·max(0, dE/dt)² to the loss to enforce thermodynamic consistency and stabilize long-time integration. (7) Gradient clipping to prevent explosion from the cubic nonlinearity.",
