  "answer": {
    "Problem Formalization": "The governing equations are the 2D incompressible Navier-Stokes system: momentum (∂u/∂t + u·∇u = -∇p/ρ + ν∇²u) and continuity (∇·u = 0), over an unspecified spatial domain Ω and time interval [0,T]. Unknowns are velocity (u,v) and pressure p. Observations consist of sparse/partial velocity measurements at select spatiotemporal points; pressure is entirely unobserved. Boundary and initial conditions are partially available. Missing specifications that affect the workflow: (1) domain geometry and dimension—determines boundary treatment and stream-function compatibility; (2) kinematic viscosity ν or Reynolds number—governs flow regime and numerical stiffness; (3) which velocity components are observed where—determines observability of the flow; (4) which boundaries have prescribed conditions (no-slip, inflow, etc.)—determines well-posedness; (5) time horizon and initial velocity field completeness. The pressure is indeterminate up to a gauge: taking the divergence of momentum and imposing ∇·u=0 yields a Poisson equation ∇²p = -ρ∇u:∇uᵀ, so pressure is determined by the velocity field up to a harmonic function satisfying the (partial) boundary conditions. With only partial Neumann-type pressure BCs (derived from momentum at boundaries where velocity BCs are known), pressure is unique up to a spatial constant per time slice; with incomplete boundary data, additional harmonic modes may remain undetermined. The workflow adds a gauge-fixing condition (zero-mean pressure at each time slice) and couples pressure to velocity through the momentum residual, which constrains the pressure gradient wherever velocity observations and physics residuals are active.",
    "Physics Constraints": "Three physics constraints are enforced: (1) Momentum balance—residual of both components of the NS momentum equation evaluated at collocation points in the interior and at boundaries where conditions are known; (2) Incompressibility—enforced by construction via a stream-function parameterization (see Model Choice), guaranteeing ∇·u = 0 to machine precision; (3) Partial boundary and initial conditions—imposed as soft constraints at known locations. Because incompressibility is enforced by construction (u = ∂ψ/∂y, v = -∂ψ/∂x), there is no divergence drift to monitor. If a penalty approach were used instead, divergence drift would be monitored by tracking the L² norm of ∇·u on a dense validation grid at each epoch, with an adaptive penalty weight that increases when the divergence norm exceeds a threshold (e.g., 10⁻⁴), and a hard stop if it exceeds a safety bound (e.g., 10⁻²). The penalty approach is rejected here because divergence-free construction eliminates an entire failure mode and reduces the number of independent loss terms requiring balancing.",
    "Model Choice": "A neural network parameterizes the stream function ψ(x,y,t;θ_ψ), yielding velocity by construction as u = ∂ψ/∂y, v = -∂ψ/∂x, which guarantees ∇·u = 0 identically. A separate network p(x,y,t;θ_p) parameterizes pressure. Both networks use modified MLPs with Fourier feature embeddings to capture multiscale spatial structures and sinusoidal time embeddings. The stream-function approach is chosen because: (a) it eliminates divergence drift entirely, removing a failure mode; (b) it reduces the number of PDE residual equations from three to two (only momentum components), simplifying loss balancing; (c) it is natural for 2D incompressible flow. The trade-off is that momentum residuals then involve third-order spatial derivatives of ψ, requiring higher-order automatic differentiation and smoother network outputs—mitigated by using sufficiently smooth activation functions (e.g., tanh or sin) and moderate depth. The pressure network is necessary because pressure cannot be extracted from the stream function alone; it is coupled to ψ through the momentum residual. A gauge condition p_mean(t) = 0 (zero spatial mean of pressure at each time) is enforced as an additional soft constraint to remove the constant-pressure null mode.",
    "Training Strategy": "The total loss is L = λ_data·L_data + λ_mom·L_mom + λ_bc·L_bc + λ_ic·L_ic + λ_gauge·L_gauge, where: L_data = MSE of predicted vs. observed velocities at measurement points; L_mom = MSE of momentum equation residuals at interior collocation points; L_bc = MSE of boundary condition residuals at known-boundary points; L_ic = MSE of initial condition residuals at known initial-time points; L_gauge = (mean_x,y[p])² at each time slice. Collocation points are sampled via a hybrid strategy: Latin hypercube sampling in (x,y,t) for broad coverage, plus denser sampling near known boundaries and observation locations, resampled every N epochs to avoid overfitting to a fixed set. Loss weights λ are initialized with λ_data = 1, λ_mom = 1, λ_bc = 10, λ_ic = 10, λ_gauge = 1, and adapted using a gradient-balancing scheme (e.g., GradNorm or manual scheduling based on relative loss magnitudes). Optimization uses Adam (lr=10⁻³) for the first 10k epochs followed by L-BFGS for fine convergence. A curriculum strategy trains first on data-only loss to initialize velocity, then gradually ramps up physics losses. For the pressure network, an alternative initialization is computed by solving the pressure Poisson equation on a coarse grid using the initial velocity fit, then interpolating to initialize θ_p—this provides a physically grounded starting point and reduces spurious pressure modes.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "Three key validation failure risks and their detection: (1) Spurious pressure mode—a harmonic pressure field p_harm satisfying ∇²p_harm = 0 with ∇p_harm ≈ 0 at observation locations would leave the velocity fit unchanged while corrupting pressure. Detection: (a) solve the eigenvalue problem for the Laplacian on Ω with the available (partial) BCs to identify near-null harmonic modes; (b) add each such mode to the predicted pressure and verify that L_data does not change—if it does not, the mode is unobservable from velocity data alone; (c) check the pressure Poisson equation residual ∇²p + ρ∇u:∇uᵀ independently on a validation grid—a spurious harmonic mode will not violate this equation only if it is truly harmonic, so a nonzero Poisson residual flags inconsistency; (d) compare pressure predictions under different gauge conditions (e.g., pinning p at different points); disagreement beyond a constant indicates an unresolved harmonic mode. (2) Under-determined velocity due to sparse observations—the velocity field may not be uniquely determined in unobserved regions. Detection: ensemble training from different random seeds; variance across ensembles identifies regions of high uncertainty. (3) Missing boundary/initial condition information leading to multiple physically consistent solutions. Detection: train with different plausible completions of missing BCs and compare solutions; large sensitivity indicates ill-posedness that must be resolved with additional data or stronger priors. The most critical risk is (1), because it is specific to the pressure-unobservability structure of incompressible flow and cannot be detected by velocity metrics alone."
  }
}
