    "Physics Constraints": "Three sets of physics constraints are enforced: (1) PDE residual: |∇²u_sc + k²u_sc|² = 0 throughout Ω, ensuring the scattered field satisfies the Helmholtz equation. (2) Sound-hard (Neumann) BC on obstacle surfaces: |∂u_sc/∂n + ∂u_inc/∂n|² = 0 on Γ_obs, enforcing zero normal velocity on rigid walls. (3) Radiation condition on the truncation boundary: a first-order absorbing boundary condition (ABC) |∂u_sc/∂n − iku_sc|² = 0 on Γ_∞ approximates the Sommerfeld radiation condition lim_{r→∞} √r(∂u_sc/∂r − iku_sc) = 0. To more effectively prevent outgoing waves from re-entering, a perfectly matched layer (PML) of thickness d is appended outside Γ_∞: within the PML, the Helmholtz equation is modified via complex coordinate stretching (e.g., x̃ = ∫₀ˣ(1 + iσ(s)/ω)ds with a smooth profile σ(s) ramping from 0 at the PML inner boundary to σ_max at the outer boundary), and a homogeneous Dirichlet condition u_sc = 0 is imposed at the outer PML edge. The PML is reflectionless in the continuous limit and exponentially damps outgoing waves, preventing re-entry.",
    "Model Choice": "A physics-informed neural network (PINN) is chosen, representing u_sc as a complex-valued field via two real-valued networks (or one network with two outputs) for Re(u_sc) and Im(u_sc). This suits the elliptic Helmholtz PDE with scattered-field formulation, where all constraints are local (PDE residual, Neumann BCs, ABC/PML equations) and no time-stepping is needed. Fourier feature embeddings are applied to the input coordinates to mitigate spectral bias and better resolve oscillatory solutions at wavenumber k. The network must handle the complex maze geometry; this is addressed by sampling densely near obstacle surfaces using the signed-distance function and within narrow corridors. The PML region is included as part of the computational domain with the modified Helmholtz equation enforced there. Alternative: a hybrid FEM–PINN approach where FEM handles the interior and the PINN enforces the ABC, but the pure PINN is selected for geometric flexibility with the maze obstacles. Missing specification: if k is large (high-frequency regime), the network may require multi-scale architectures or domain decomposition to resolve the oscillations.",
